In Week 13 of Trump\'92s second term, a pattern that had been faint in earlier weeks came into sharp relief. The presidency was no longer merely stretching its reach; it was testing whether the other branches would, in practice, be able to stop it. Immigration, higher education, civil rights enforcement, and the information system itself became the main fields of contest. The week\'92s events showed a government willing to treat law as a tool rather than a boundary, and to use money, status, and fear to bring once\uc0\u8209 independent institutions to heel. Yet the same week also recorded judges, universities, and some state officials pushing back, insisting that orders be obeyed and rights respected. The struggle was not abstract. It played out in prisons in El Salvador, in classrooms in Maine and Virginia, in clinics in Alabama, and in the quiet offices of civil servants told they could now be fired at will. It felt close to home.\
\
At the start of Week 13, the Democracy Clock stood at 7:49 p.m. By the end of the period, it had moved to 7:50 p.m., a shift of 1.1 minutes toward midnight. The movement was modest in numerical terms, but it reflected a dense cluster of structural changes. Executive power widened again through new orders and memoranda that bypassed normal process. Law was used more openly as a weapon against critics and vulnerable groups, not as a limit on state action. Agencies were hollowed out or bent toward private and partisan aims. Transparency was cut back, and the civil service was made more precarious. At the same time, courts blocked some deportations, paused the gutting of the consumer watchdog, and insisted that a wrongfully deported man must be brought home. The clock moved because the balance between assertion and restraint shifted further toward assertion, even as resistance remained visible. Both trends mattered.\
\
The clearest test of the rule of law centered on one man, Kilmar \'c1brego Garc\'eda, a Maryland resident wrongly deported to El Salvador. The Supreme Court had already ruled, unanimously, that the government must facilitate his return and treat his case as if the deportation had never happened. Yet the administration told lower courts that it had no legal duty to bring him back, and that any attempt to do so would intrude on the president\'92s foreign affairs powers. In the Oval Office, President Trump met with El Salvador\'92s president, Nayib Bukele, and the two leaders agreed that Garc\'eda would not be returned, despite the Court\'92s order. Administration lawyers argued that once a person was in Salvadoran custody, U.S. courts had no jurisdiction. A federal judge in Maryland rebuked this stance, noting that \'93nothing has been done\'94 to comply, and opened a two\uc0\u8209 week fact\u8209 finding inquiry into possible contempt. The Fourth Circuit refused to block the district court\'92s order, warning that allowing the executive to detain residents in foreign prisons beyond judicial reach would endanger constitutional democracy itself. The law, on paper, held firm. In practice, the executive treated it as one voice among many.\
\
The same pattern appeared in the administration\'92s use of the Alien Enemies Act to deport Venezuelan migrants to El Salvador\'92s mega\uc0\u8209 prison. Judges in Nevada, California, and Colorado issued temporary orders blocking specific deportations and halting the broader program while lawsuits proceeded. One judge, James Boasberg, found probable cause to hold officials in criminal contempt for ignoring his injunction and failing to recall deportation flights. He warned that if the government did not \'93purge\'94 its contempt by returning those removed, he would consider appointing an independent prosecutor. The administration responded with an emergency motion arguing that contempt proceedings themselves were unconstitutional. Here again, courts asserted their authority, but enforcement depended on whether the executive would accept real consequences for defiance. The clock moved because the question was no longer whether judges would issue orders, but whether those orders would bite. That is a different kind of test.\
\
Immigration enforcement more broadly became a tool for punishing speech and identity. A Palestinian organizer and Columbia graduate, Mahmoud Khalil, was deemed deportable based on a State Department memo about his beliefs and associations, with no criminal allegations. A Turkish PhD student at Tufts, R\'fcmeysa \'d6zt\'fcrk, lost her visa and was detained in Louisiana after co\uc0\u8209 authoring an op\u8209 ed about Gaza; an immigration judge denied her bail as a supposed danger to the community. Mohsen Mahdawi, a Palestinian green\u8209 card holder and Columbia student, was arrested by ICE during his naturalization interview in Vermont, in what his lawyers called retaliation for pro\u8209 Palestinian advocacy. A Turkish student who criticized a university\'92s Gaza stance was deported despite no evidence of ties to terrorism. In each case, immigration law, designed to regulate entry and status, was used to target dissenting voices. The line between national security and political policing blurred. That line matters. When it moves, whole communities learn that speech can cost them their place.\
\
The administration also pushed the boundaries of who counts as deportable and where they can be sent. Merwil Guti\'e9rrez, a 19\uc0\u8209 year\u8209 old Venezuelan with no gang ties, was swept up with hundreds of others and sent to El Salvador under the Alien Enemies Act, to a prison in a country with which he had no connection. The government argued that once deportees were in Salvadoran custody, U.S. courts could not order their return. At the same time, President Trump proposed deporting \'93homegrown criminals,\'94 including U.S. citizens, to El Salvador for imprisonment, an idea legal experts described as plainly unconstitutional. The administration began vetting the social media of all visa applicants who had visited Gaza since 2007, singling out a political geography for special scrutiny. Together, these moves pointed toward an immigration and citizenship regime stratified by origin, ideology, and perceived loyalty, with foreign prisons used as an extension of U.S. power. The structure of belonging itself was being revised.\
\
Against this backdrop, courts did not simply stand aside. A federal judge in Boston blocked the administration\'92s attempt to cancel a parole program that gave legal status and work permits to more than 500,000 migrants from Cuba, Nicaragua, Venezuela, and Haiti. Judges in Colorado and elsewhere halted deportations of Venezuelans under the Alien Enemies Act. Another judge barred a new policy that would have allowed rapid deportations to third countries without any chance to show fear of persecution, torture, or death. In Arizona and Florida, wrongfully detained U.S. citizens were released after judges dismissed cases or state authorities relented. These rulings did not reverse the structural changes in how immigration power was conceived, but they showed that the judiciary still functioned as a brake, even if it now had to fight for compliance. The brake worked, but under strain.\
\
While the courts wrestled with deportations, the administration turned its attention to universities and schools as ideological battlegrounds. Harvard University became the central target. After Harvard refused to accept a set of federal demands\'97ending diversity, equity, and inclusion programs, reshaping admissions and hiring, cracking down on pro\uc0\u8209 Palestinian protests, and cooperating more closely with immigration enforcement\'97the Department of Education froze roughly $2.3 billion in grants and a $60 million contract. The White House threatened to strip Harvard of its tax\u8209 exempt status, and the IRS was reported to be preparing such a move, despite expert warnings that presidential direction of tax enforcement would be illegal. Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem demanded records on foreign students allegedly involved in \'93dangerous or violent activity,\'94 threatening the university\'92s ability to host international students. Harvard\'92s leadership publicly rejected the demands, citing constitutional protections and academic freedom. The funding freeze remained in place. The message to other institutions was clear. Federal money, tax status, and visa programs could be used to force compliance with the administration\'92s cultural agenda.\
\
The pressure did not stop at Harvard. The Department of Energy faced a lawsuit from universities over a policy change that would cut research funding, and the NAACP sued the administration over anti\uc0\u8209 DEI policies in schools, arguing that they violated the Civil Rights Act. Twelve students in Pentagon\u8209 run schools, supported by the ACLU, sued Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth over book bans that removed works on race, gender, and health from their libraries. At the U.S. Naval Academy, nearly 400 books about slavery, the civil rights movement, and the Holocaust were taken off shelves under a DEI ban, while Hitler\'92s \'93Mein Kampf\'94 remained. These actions, rooted in executive orders, did more than censor particular titles. They signaled a federal project to reshape what young people, especially those in military\u8209 linked institutions, are allowed to learn about the country\'92s past and present. When the state curates memory in this way, it narrows the space in which future citizens can judge their own government. That is the point.\
\
K\'9612 education became another front. In Maine, the administration sued to stop transgender girls from competing in girls\'92 sports, arguing that the state\'92s policy violated Title IX. President Trump and Attorney General Pam Bondi threatened to withhold $250 million in federal K\'9612 funding and freeze school lunch money unless Maine changed its law. A federal judge temporarily blocked the funding freeze after Maine countersued, but the threat remained. At the same time, the president signed an earlier executive order barring transgender participants from women\'92s sports nationwide, and visa restrictions were placed on transgender athletes entering the United States. These moves used federal spending and immigration tools to enforce a particular view of gender across states and borders. They also showed how civil rights enforcement could be inverted. The Department of Justice\'92s Civil Rights Division, under new leadership, issued mission statements that downplayed traditional protections for marginalized groups and emphasized voter fraud, \'93anti\uc0\u8209 white\'94 discrimination, and enforcement of Trump\'92s orders. The machinery stayed in place, but its purpose shifted.\
