Voting itself came under new pressure. President Trump issued an executive order requiring documentary proof of citizenship to vote in federal elections, despite the lack of evidence that noncitizen voting is a significant problem. The U.S. House passed the Save Act, which would require such proof for voter registration and limit registration by mail or online. In North Carolina, courts invalidated hundreds of ballots in a close state supreme court race based on residency challenges brought by the losing candidate, Jefferson Griffin, including ballots from overseas and military voters. An appellate court sided with Griffin in a broader challenge that could force tens of thousands of voters to prove their eligibility after the fact, though the ruling was on hold pending state supreme court review. The state Board of Elections, responding to investigative reporting, moved to restore ballots that had been wrongly discarded and to verify residency through its own methods. Across these cases, the language of \'93election integrity\'94 was used to justify new barriers and retroactive challenges, while the actual instances of fraud remained vanishingly small. The effect was to make voting more burdensome for many, especially those with fewer documents or more mobile lives.\
\
Beyond law and education, the administration worked to reshape the machinery of government itself. A new category of federal workers\'97about 50,000 positions\'97was created as at\uc0\u8209 will employees who could be fired for \'93subversion of presidential directives.\'94 This change cut into long\u8209 standing civil service protections and made it easier to remove career officials who resisted political pressure. At the Department of Homeland Security and other agencies, roughly 50 senior staff, including FEMA\'92s acting administrator, were subjected to polygraph tests in leak investigations. Dan Caldwell, a top adviser to Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth, was escorted from the Pentagon and placed on leave over an alleged unauthorized disclosure. An immigration lawyer who had admitted in court that Garc\'eda\'92s deportation was a mistake was fired by the Justice Department. Together, these actions sent a message inside the bureaucracy: loyalty to the president\'92s line mattered more than adherence to process or candor before the courts. Whistleblowing and internal dissent carried real risk. That risk was the point.\
\
Administrative agencies were also steered toward private and partisan interests. A presidential memorandum allowed agencies to repeal regulations they deemed \'93obviously unlawful\'94 without public notice, weakening the notice\uc0\u8209 and\u8209 comment process that anchors modern rulemaking. Executive orders directed sweeping changes in procurement, office siting, and critical mineral policy, centralizing more discretion in the White House. The Department of Government Efficiency, led by Elon Musk, tried to embed staff inside the Vera Institute of Justice, an independent nonprofit, even after canceling its federal funding, framing the move as compliance with an executive order. At the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, the administration moved to fire nearly 90 percent of staff after a court ruled the agency could be shrunk but not abolished. A federal judge, Amy Berman Jackson, blocked the layoffs, and another judge later paused them, but the attempt itself showed how far the executive was willing to go to disable a watchdog created by Congress. In the financial sector, the Securities and Exchange Commission dropped or paused investigations into more than a dozen cryptocurrency firms while the Trump family expanded its stake in the industry through World Liberty Financial. Trump Media and Technology Group launched \'93Truth Social\u8209 branded\'94 investment accounts designed to profit from companies favored by the president\'92s tariffs and \'93America First\'94 policies. Policy and profit were no longer merely adjacent; they were intertwined.\
