Information and memory were managed with equal care. The administration closed the State Department\'92s Counter Foreign Information Manipulation and Interference office, known as R/FIMI, which had tracked foreign disinformation campaigns. Secretary of State Marco Rubio framed the closure as a move against domestic \'93censorship,\'94 but the effect was to remove a dedicated capacity to monitor and counter hostile influence operations. Climate and environmental justice webpages, including tools that mapped pollution and climate impacts, were taken down from federal sites, prompting lawsuits from environmental and consumer groups. Covid.gov, once a portal for tests, vaccines, and treatment information, was replaced with content focused on the \'93lab leak\'94 theory and attacks on Dr. Anthony Fauci, the World Health Organization, and state leaders. The White House website published an article accusing NPR and PBS of running a \'93grift\'94 of \'93radical, woke propaganda.\'94 The administration misrepresented the Supreme Court\'92s ruling in Garc\'eda\'92s case, claiming victory where it had been ordered to act. It then posted an edited image of a New York Times front page, removing the word \'93wrongly\'94 from a description of Garc\'eda\'92s deportation and adding the phrase \'93who is never coming back.\'94 These acts did not simply spin events; they altered the official record and signaled that the government would use its platforms to rewrite ongoing disputes in its favor.\
