Independent media faced direct pressure. The Associated Press, having won a court order restoring its White House access after refusing to adopt the term \'93Gulf of America,\'94 found its reporter and photographer barred from an Oval Office event. The AP accused the administration of violating the injunction. President Trump called for CBS to lose its broadcasting license after \'9360 Minutes\'94 aired segments he disliked, and urged FCC Chair Brendan Carr to impose maximum fines. Carr, in turn, threatened Comcast, the parent of MSNBC and CNN, over coverage of the Garc\'eda story, suggesting that their reporting might violate the requirement that licensees serve the public interest. A Trump ally reportedly told CNN\'92s parent company that it could avoid lawsuits by producing favorable content, such as a documentary about Melania Trump. These moves used the tools of regulation and litigation as levers over coverage. They also reinforced a hierarchy in which state\uc0\u8209 aligned outlets thrived while critical ones faced legal and economic risk. The chill was intentional.\
