Economic policy added another layer of instability. On what he called \'93liberation day,\'94 President Trump announced a 10 percent universal tariff on all imports, followed by steep \'93reciprocal\'94 tariffs on China and the European Union. Markets plunged; the Dow fell by more than 2,000 points, and global investors began selling U.S. bonds, driving up yields even as the dollar weakened. Within days, the administration paused most of the tariffs for 90 days, except for China, whose rate was raised to 125 or 145 percent, depending on the account. U.S. Customs quietly exempted smartphones and other electronics from the China tariffs, shielding a major import category without public explanation. The Commerce Department imposed a 21 percent tariff on Mexican tomatoes, risking higher food prices. China responded by cutting off exports of key rare earth minerals and halting Boeing deliveries. Economists warned of recession and inflation. The Federal Reserve, under Jerome Powell, refused to cut interest rates in response to political pressure, citing data and the need for independence. President Trump attacked Powell as \'93always TOO LATE AND WRONG\'94 and called for his firing, even though he lacked the legal authority to remove the chair without cause. The pattern was not one of steady industrial strategy but of abrupt moves and reversals that created chaos, then used that chaos to justify further concentration of decision\uc0\u8209 making in the executive.\
