Amid these shifts, civil society and some officials continued to act. Senator Chris Van Hollen of Maryland wrote to El Salvador\'92s ambassador, then traveled to El Salvador to seek access to Garc\'eda and press for his return. Salvadoran authorities denied him a meeting with President Bukele and initially blocked access to Garc\'eda, but he eventually met the detainee and relayed his messages home. Congressman Gerald Connolly, the ranking member on the House Oversight Committee, demanded that the Social Security Administration reverse its freeze of the Enumeration Beyond Entry program, arguing that it increased costs, reduced efficiency, and might violate federal law. Labor groups sued over the cancellation of international labor rights grants. Environmental organizations challenged the rollback of green policies and the removal of climate data. Students, universities, and civil rights groups went to court over visa revocations, book bans, and anti\uc0\u8209 DEI rules. These actions did not stop the week\'92s drift, but they kept open channels through which law and public pressure could still work. Those channels remain vital.\
\
Looking ahead from Week 13, several processes were already in motion. The Supreme Court set arguments for May on the president\'92s executive order seeking to end birthright citizenship, a case that would test the meaning of the Fourteenth Amendment. Federal judges launched inquiries into the administration\'92s defiance of deportation orders and signaled possible criminal contempt. Lawsuits over Harvard\'92s funding freeze, Maine\'92s education funds, the CFPB layoffs, climate grants, and DEI bans were moving through the courts. The closure of the State Department\'92s disinformation office left a gap in the country\'92s defenses against foreign influence, with no clear replacement. Tariff disputes with China and lawsuits from California over trade authority promised further clashes over who controls economic policy. These were not speculative risks. They were scheduled hearings, pending motions, and open investigations that would shape the next stages of the struggle over power.\
\
By the close of Week 13, with the Democracy Clock at 7:50 p.m., the civic covenant described in the moral assessment had not shattered, but it had cracked further. Executive orders and memoranda were used to bypass process and concentrate authority. Law was bent to serve the state\'92s immediate aims, especially in immigration and civil rights. Agencies meant to serve the public were hollowed out or steered toward private and partisan ends. Transparency tools were removed, archives were sealed or altered, and the information space was flooded with state\uc0\u8209 driven narratives. Universities, schools, and media organizations were told that their funding, tax status, and access depended on their willingness to align with the administration\'92s agenda. Yet courts still issued orders, some states still resisted, and parts of civil society still organized and sued. The week matters in the larger arc of the term because it shows both how far the executive is prepared to go, and how much strain the remaining guardrails can bear. The time is not yet late enough that reversal is impossible. But with each small movement of the clock, the cost of repair grows, and the habit of defiance becomes more normal. The official time at the end of Week 13 is 7:50 p.m. The distance to midnight is shorter, and the work of holding the line is harder than it was a week before.\
